Week 13 – Time to event data lab

Drew Tyre

November 12, 2016

In this weeks lab you’ll explore a dataset collected by Mitch Bern on the attack behavior of spiders. Each spider was placed in an arena with a prey item (cricket) that was either tasty or not tasty, and provided with cues (vibration or no vibration). This trial was repeated for each individual 9 times. The question is whether or not the presence of an unrelated cue (the vibration) speeds up learning. The response is latency to attack measured in seconds; trials were terminated at 900 seconds so there are censored observations.

ggplot(spiders, aes(x = trial, y = lat.attack)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() + 
    facet_wrap(~treatment, labeller = labeller(treatment = trt.longnames)) + 
    geom_line(aes(group = animal))

Attack latency in seconds across trials by treatment. Thin black lines join points representing the same spider. There is quite a lot of overplotting. Smooth curves show expected latency by trial assuming censored individuals attack at 900 seconds.

As you can see in the scatterplots, spiders in the Not Tasty treatments do take longer to attack the prey as trials progress. However there is alot of variation among individual spiders. Some spiders offered tasty prey simply didn’t attack for several trials, and another spider in the no vibration not tasty treatment always attacked quickly! Behavioral ecologists worry alot about anthropomorphizing, so to avoid this potential bias Mitch called the treatments Blue, Purple, Yellow and Orange. This is fine, but makes it a bit hard to test for interactions between the two seperate experimental factors. The statistical version of Mitch’s hypothesis is an interaction between trial and treatment. You can see the correspondence between the colors and the experimental treatments using the variable “vd”:

with(spiders, table(treatment, vd))
##          vd
## treatment nn ny yn yy
##    Blue   72  0  0  0
##    Orange  0  0  0 99
##    Purple  0  0 81  0
##    Yellow  0 81  0  0

The first letter is y/n for vibration, and the second is y/n for distastful (so ‘y’ is not tasty).

  1. Thinking about mean latency to attack in our regular lm() framework, how would mean latency change with a distasteful by vibration interaction? Think about trial 0 compared to trial 8 in each treatment.

In trial 0 there should be no differences between the treatments, because all spiders have no experience with different types of prey. By trial 8, latency to attack should be greater in treatments with distasteful prey, while there should be no change in treatments with tasty prey. If the extra vibration signal increases learning rate, latency to attack will be even longer or longer at earlier trials when both vibration and distasteful prey are present.

  1. Use lm() to fit the model lat.attack ~ distasteful * vibration * trial model. Check the residuals. Does the mean latency change as you expected? Is there a significant interaction?
globallm <- lm(lat.attack ~ distasteful * vibration * trial, data = spiders)
rr <- broom::augment(globallm)
rr1 <- ggplot(rr, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() + 
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = 2)

# get int and slope for qqline
probs <- c(0.25, 0.75)
y <- quantile(rr$.resid, probs, names = FALSE, na.rm = TRUE)
x <- qnorm(probs)
slope <- diff(y)/diff(x)
int <- y[1L] - slope * x[1L]
rr2 <- ggplot(rr, aes(sample = .resid)) + geom_qq(size = rel(4)) + geom_abline(intercept = int, 
    slope = slope, linetype = 2, size = 2)

rr3 <- ggplot(rr, aes(x = .fitted, y = sqrt(abs(.std.resid)))) + geom_point() + 
    geom_smooth() + geom_hline(yintercept = 1)

rr4 <- ggplot(rr, aes(x = trial, y = .resid)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth() + 
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = 2)

# the :: means I don't have to do library(gridExtra) to get at the function
# -- handy if I only want it once.
gridExtra::grid.arrange(rr1, rr2, rr3, rr4)

So the experiment isn’t a total loss. Average Latency at trial 0 in the nn treatment is 223 seconds, and the increase of 8.7 seconds with each additional trial is not significant, as expected. Experiencing distasteful prey increases latency to attack by 41 seconds with each additional trial. Experiencing vibration also increases latency to attack by 27 seconds with each additional trial, a smaller amount than experiencing distasteful prey. The effects of distasteful prey and vibration are additive. That is, there is no evidence that learning is faster in the presence of multiple cues. Note that using the treatment variable instead of distasteful*vibration makes it much harder to reach this conclusion. In addition, if censored observations are removed instead of being treated as event at 900 seconds, the entire model is not significant.

So the first thing to do is to get some survival curves. We’ve actually got a repeated measures or mixed effects situation here with individuals representing our groups, but we’ll ignore that for the moment. The variable ``att’’ is 0 if the spider didn’t attack, and 1 if it did - so it acts as a censoring indicator.

ggplot(spiders, aes(x = factor(att), y = lat.attack)) + geom_boxplot()

All the individuals with att == 0 had latencies of 900 seconds; they never attacked. We start survival analysis by calculating Kaplan-Meier survivorship curves.

library(survival)
# On the LHS of formula the response is a Surv() object the first argument
# is the time of the event the second argument is the censoring indicator 1
# if the event occurred, or 0 if the observation is censored at that point
# only use the trial 0 data
spiders.km0 <- survfit(Surv(lat.attack, att) ~ treatment, data = spiders[spiders$trial == 
    0, ])

# there is a plot() method for these objects
plot(spiders.km0, col = c("Blue", "Orange", "Purple", "Yellow"), lwd = 3, main = "Trial 0", 
    xlim = c(0, 900))
# manually add a legend, base graphics style
loc <- legend("topright", legend = rep(c("No Vibration", "Vibration"), times = 2), 
    lwd = 3, col = c("Blue", "Purple", "Yellow", "Orange"), bty = "n", ncol = 2, 
    xjust = 0.5, inset = 0.05)
# use the return value of legend() to figure out where the columns are
ypos = 2 * loc$text$y[1] - loc$text$y[2]
# Add the Tasty not Tasty above the columns
text(loc$text$x[c(1, 3)], ypos, labels = c("Tasty", "Not"), adj = 0)

# do it for trial 8
spiders.km8 = survfit(Surv(lat.attack, att) ~ treatment, data = spiders[spiders$trial == 
    8, ])
plot(spiders.km8, col = c("Blue", "Orange", "Purple", "Yellow"), lwd = 3, main = "Trial 8", 
    xlim = c(0, 900))

As we might expect, it looks like there are no differences between treatments on the first trial, while on the 8th trial there are substantial differences. These differences were undetectable until the censored trials were properly accounted for.

So lets try a Cox proportional hazards model with trial and treatment as covariates. A cox model assumes that the variables are simply multiplying the baseline hazard. I will set Individual as a cluster variable - equivalent to specifying a random effect in a mixed effects model. In a Cox model this estimates a different baseline hazard function for each individual.

spiders.ph1 <- coxph(Surv(lat.attack, att) ~ treatment * trial + cluster(animal), 
    data = spiders)
summary(spiders.ph1)

So compared to Blue, treatments Orange and Yellow have reduced hazards (negative coefficients) with increasing trial. Orange and Yellow treatments have distasteful prey, and Orange has both vibration and distasteful prey. Treatment Purple (vibration only) also has a reduced hazard with increasing trial but the coefficient is not significantly different from zero.

It is difficult to directly interpret the coefficients in the summary table. The columns labelled exp(coef) can be interpreted as the proportional change in the baseline hazard. So, the baseline hazard drops by ~5% (0.95) for each additional trial in the Blue treatment, but the confidence limits on that number include 1 (no change in hazard). Treatment Orange looks like a 45% increase in hazard at trial 0, but again the confidence limits include zero. Individuals in the orange treatment have a hazard reducing by 28% with each additional trial, and the confidence limits there do not include zero.

Before we get too carried away interpreting this model we need to check the assumptions using complementary log-log plots and log survival plots. To do this we can either use the survfit objects we created above, or make some new ones from the fitted Cox model. We can also use cox.zph() function to get a test from the model itself. Remember the lines should be straight and parallel on the complementary log-log plot for the proportional hazards assumption, and straight and parallel on the cumulative hazard plot for accelerated failure time. I’m a bit lazy so I will use the builtin plot method for survfit objects.

cox.zph(spiders.ph1)  # looks OK

    lwd = 3, main = "Trial 8", xlim = c(1, 900), ylab = "Cumulative Hazard")

So this is all good - we can’t use accelerated failure time, and the proportional hazards assumption looks OK.

  1. Can we simplify this model? If so, continue with backwards selection until you have the simplest model.

We cannot simplify this model because removing the treatment by trial interaction changes the likelihood by an amount that is very unlikely to occur by chance (p < 0.001) if the interaction was not important.

That’s a nice plot, but what a lot of work! Making prediction plots from survival objects remains a difficult task.

If you look at the plots of latency in trial 8, it looks like vibration on its own deters attack (purple higher than blue) although the confidence levels nearly include the other curve. In addition, there doesn’t seem to be any difference between the curves for Orange and Yellow (distasteful prey), because the confidence levels overlap widely. So perhaps there’s no interaction between vibration and non-tasty prey - maybe they are just adding together to deter attack. This plot looks quite different from the Survivorship plot constructed above, where Orange had quite a bit larger survival. The difference could be due to treating trial as a linear covariate in the Cox model.

  1. Try a different Cox model using a three way interaction between variables vibration, distasteful, and trial to test this idea. Simplify it as far as possible using backwards selection. Does this improve your ability to test the biological hypothesis?

So we loose the three way interaction and the distasteful by vibration interaction. There is no magnification of learning by including multiple cues. This is the same conclusion we came to with the lm() model, although our estimates of expected time to attack will be unbiased here. Getting the structure of the predictor variables correct is more important to reaching the right conclusion than treating the response variable correctly.
